Barack Obama will be the fourth US President to receive the Nobel Peace Prize
U.S. President Barack Obama will fly to Oslo, Norway, to spend 26 hours there and be the fourth U.S. president in history to receive the Nobel Peace Prize.
The $1.4 million diploma, medal and cheque will be awarded to him, among other things, for his outstanding efforts to strengthen global diplomacy and collaboration among nations.
The White House leader and his wife Michelle will land in the morning in the Norwegian metropolis and have a busy program.
He will first visit the Nobel Institute, where he will meet for the very first time the five members of the Committee who chose him in October from 172 people and 33 organizations.
The presidential couple's schedule then includes an interview with Norway's King Harald V and Queen Sonja.
The visit will culminate in the afternoon at a solemn ceremony where Obama will receive the prestigious award.
He will be the fourth American president to receive it, but only the third who will be awarded the prize in the Committee itself.
The White House informed in advance that Obama would talk about the war in Afghanistan at the award ceremony.
The president does not want to avoid this because he is aware that he receives this award by being a president who is waging a war in two countries at the present time.
He reinforced the war effort a few days ago by sending additional units to Afghanistan, which none of his critics will forget to stress.
During the ceremony, Obama will also receive a gold medal, a diploma and a cheque for ten million Swedish kronor (about 1.1 million Euros).
He intends to donate it to charitable organizations, but he has not yet decided in concrete terms which ones.
His busy program will then take him and his wife to a banquet including, in addition to the king and queen of Norway, the head of government and 250 other guests.
Obama was rather reluctant to do so at first.
He mentioned, for example, that he felt that he did not deserve it fully.
He also repeated several times that this is not a price for himself alone, but for all those who defend the same values as him.
As soon as the announcement was made, he said it would be an "invitation to act".
