Czech discovery: a substance that works on "hard" HIV viruses as well
A team of Czech and German scientists are testing new combinations that can slow down the spread of HIV in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also acts on viruses that have already developed drug immunity.
This reality takes precedence in some cases over the fact that the combination does not act as intensively on common variants of the virus as well as some medicines already available.
It is not possible to cure AIDS right now.
However, the lives of patients can be radically extended through a mixture of medications that prevent the spread of HIV virus in the body.
However, their consumption results in a series of side effects.
Moreover, the suppression of this multiplication has the effect of developing so-called resistant viruses on which medicines no longer have an effect.
The work of experts from three institutions, the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, the VŠCHT of Prague and the University of Heidelberg paves the way for a way to deal with the resistance of the virus.
They have shown that substances called metalocarboranes act on the protein responsible for the multiplication of the HIV virus.
Metalocarboranes are an assemblage of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
This combination blocks the development of the virus in a different way from all the medicines used so far and that is why they could overcome the problem of resistance.
The researchers' work leads them to discover new "improved" substances, based on their knowledge of the molecular mechanics of their bonds on virus proteins.
Metalocarboranes have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-wall cages are formed by boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms and connected by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
A treacherous and resistant virus.
HIV protease is an HIV virus protein that is essential to the life cycle of the virus.
Without the division of the HIV virus caused by HIV protease there would be no generation of mature infectious particles of the virus.
If HIV protease is stopped, the spread of the virus in the patient's body will also be stopped, the researchers explain in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
