Written in the country's constitution in 1978, China's single-child policy is to date, without question, the most controversial obligation introduced by the communist government.
Couples who violate this policy risk having to pay colossal fines -- up to three times their annual income -- and face discrimination in the workplace.
The Chinese authorities have assigned the duty of the police to help the country avoid a dangerous trend for its natural resources, while human rights lawyers have denounced abuses in the implementation of this policy.
In rural areas, some authorities have forced pregnant women with a second child to have abortions.
In addition, many couples have resorted to selective abortions leading to an abnormally high ratio of boys to girls.
In recent years, the authorities responsible for the population have gradually softened their position on the policy of the single child.
In 2004, they granted more exceptions to the rule -- including for urban residents, members of ethnic minorities and cases where men and women are already single children -- and in 2007, they softened a lot of their hard slogans.
Qiao Xiaochun, professor at the Institute of Population Research at the University of Beijing, said that the central government authorities have recently discussed even more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children if one of the partners is a single child.
In July, Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to encourage births.
In no time, posters encouraging families to have only one child were replaced by copies of retail regulations that have the right to have a second child and how to apply for permission.
The city's government sent family planners and volunteers to meet couples at their homes and slide flyers under their doorsteps.
He also promised to provide psychological and financial advice to those who would like to have more than one child.
According to the Family Planning Officer, the response was disappointing.
Disappointing response
Although officials in a rural city in the suburbs of Shanghai say they saw an increase in requests for couples' files wishing a second child after the campaign was launched, the more urban district reported that there was no change.
The municipality of Huinan, with a population of 115,000, for example, still receives only four to five requests per month.
Shanghai officials, disappointed, say that despite the campaign, the number of births in the city in 2010 is still expected to be only about 165,000 -- slightly higher than 2009 but less than 2008.
Feng Juying, Head of the Family Planning Committee in the municipality of Caolu of Shanghai, said that financial considerations are probably the main reason why many people do not want to have more children.
They want to provide their first child, she said.
Yang Jiawei, 27, and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26, said they would love to have two children and that they are legally allowed to do so.
But like many Chinese, they only have the minimum health insurance and life insurance provided by the government.
Without social protection, they say, the decision would be irresponsible.
Westerners mistakenly consider the single child policy to be a rights issue," said Yang, a construction engineer whose wife is seven months pregnant with the couple's first child.
It's true, we're being robbed of the chance to have more than one child.
But the problem is not just the law.
It's the money.
Other couples cite psychological reasons for their hesitation.
Wang, Head of Human Resources, said she only wanted a single child because she was one of them herself. "We were the center of the family and used to have everyone look after us."
We're not used to taking care of anyone else and we really don't want to take care of others."
Chen Zijian, 42 years old and owner of a translation company, says it more earnestly.
For middle-class couples working together, who lower the birth rate, he said, one must be selfish to succeed.
People 20 or 30 years old grew up watching their parents fight in the early days of capitalist China and do not want to have this lifestyle themselves, he says.
Even one child takes a lot of time from his parents, he says.
A mother must give up at least two years of her social life.
Then there are the space problems -- "You have to change your apartment" -- and the planning -- "When your child is only 9 months old, you have to write his resume to get a place in the best kindergarten."
Most of his friends are ready for this experience once, says Chen, but not two.
Our generation is the first to enjoy a higher standard of living, he says.
We don't want to make too many sacrifices.
The United Nations group has draft emission reduction plans
The UN-sponsored climate conference -- characterized so far by disorganized assignments and mutual recriminations -- has returned to the spotlight on Friday, due to the publication of a document highlighting ambitious greenhouse gas reductions over the next 40 years, with industrialized nations shouldering most of the burden, in the coming days.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, highlighted the remaining obstacles, as much as it informed the way forward.
But it was seen as an important step forward in the negotiations that are short of time, with over 100 leaders from around the world arriving next week in Copenhagen.
The text, drafted by an ad hoc working group of the United Nations, does not say how much rich countries would give to the poor to withstand global warming, both in the short and long term.
And it offers a wide range of options for key issues, including how developed economies and emerging new economies could reduce their carbon production and what would be the upper limit of global temperature increase that those responsible would be willing to tolerate.
It gives the process great flexibility, said John Coequyt, Representative in Washington of the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who drafted six pages of the document, studied a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the UN's Executive Secretary General on Climate Change, Yvo de Boer, described as "the complete picture".
It shows the guidelines for a possible agreement in which industrial nations would collectively reduce their emissions by 2020, 25 to 45 per cent from 1990 levels, while the major developing countries, over the same period, would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 per cent.
Together, countries would reduce emissions by between 50 and 95 per cent by 2050.
The European Union has also relaunched negotiations on Friday, promising to provide $3.6 billion a year over the next three years to help the poorest countries adapt to the impact of climate change -- to withstand floods and drought or to avoid deforestation.
However, on Friday, the same verbal altercations occurred, which have dominated the negotiations since last week.
Todd Stern, US Climate Negotiating Representative, rejected any discussion that required the reduction of greenhouse gases by industrialized countries, compared to the voluntary efforts of the major emerging economies, if not funded by developed countries.
This change is the signal that the Obama administration is getting harder on China than the Bush administration was two years ago.
The United States will not sign an agreement without the efforts and actions of the major developing countries, says Stern, who also regretted that the text does not insist enough to ensure that reductions could be verified by external observers.
Stern commented an hour after China's Deputy Foreign Minister He Yafei said that the US lead negotiator either lacked "good sense" or was "extremely irresponsible" for saying earlier this week that the US would not financially help China to fight global warming.
With the future economic trajectories of the world's major powers at stake, defects have emerged both within the third world and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle is more about saving individual economies than saving the planet, with China and the United States arguing about their respective obligations, while the poorer nations insist that the two dozen most influential countries ignore the scientific imperatives of more courageous action.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said that it was not surprising that the major powers were fighting to find out who would suffer the costs of reducing greenhouse gases, even though vulnerable countries had become more aggressive in their attempt to hold large emitters accountable for their actions.
It's really a game in which a new economic hegemony is developed, said Ulate, who is also Climate Advisor for Mexico and Central America for International Conservation.
Some of these countries that are more vulnerable to the impact of climate change have indicated that they will continue to put pressure on them to obtain a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although most of the main participants say that negotiations will lead to at least political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Island States, which brings together 43 members, drafted a proposal for a 24-page treaty early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, Head of the climate unit of the European Commission, said that the action of the small island states "were under political pressure on the complete political process", in part because they are now unified and are asking emerging economies such as China and India to act.
The discussions became an urgent matter, while delegates focused on the fact that they needed to resolve most of the outstanding issues before the Heads of Government reached an agreement.
High-level officials such as the Minister of the Environment of India, Jairam Ramesh and the Chinese Deputy Minister descended from their aircraft and rushed into the Bella Center building to attend closed meetings and briefings, in order to be able to make claims that would be considered in the following week.
The real image of the gathering -- at which 13,000 people enter and leave the Palais des congrès every day -- guitar activists present night shows mocking countries that, according to them, betray each other and that proposals are written and distributed on paper rather than by email -- is a real challenge.
The intensity is only increasing: almost all the important ministers are here and no later than Wednesday, 60 Heads of Government will be in Copenhagen.
We are entering the court of the greats, said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, vice-president for global policy at Conservation International.
The heavy goods vehicles are coming.
In Britain, the first train at 225 km/h will redefine Monday's syndrome
At 5:13 a.m. on Monday morning, a whistle will blow through the night to signal the departure of a train that will mark a transportation revolution in Great Britain.
The country's first high-speed commuter train will reach 225 km/h, leaving from Ashford, Kent, London St Pancras, covering 93 km in 38 minutes.
Lord Adonis, the Minister of Transport, will be joined by Lady Kelly Holmes on the first Javelin suburban train outside London.
It hopes that the new service will enable Britain to integrate an international network of fast and reliable trains and connect the major conurbations of the Midlands, North and Scotland to London.
The small lost holes will become flourishing suburban cities, the duration of business trips will be much shorter and the passage of the aircraft and car to the train will reduce national carbon emissions while reducing traffic congestion on roads.
In theory, the three main political parties adhere to this project.
But the £10 billion needed to build a new rail network, the inevitable planning battle and the fears of environmental dangers could slow down British high-speed lines.
According to The Times, High Speed Two (HS2), a company created in January to produce a feasibility report for the government, will deliver its document to Lord Adonis on December 30.
This will allow him to obtain a detailed map of the route of the next stage planned for the high-speed network.
The new line linking London to the West Midlands will be drawn within five metres of the urban area and sites where the environmental impact may be controversial.
In the countryside, the plan will be drawn up to 25 meters from the final route.
It is also expected that HS2 will present three options for a larger high-speed network, going north.
Lord Adonis will answer in the spring.
The preferred options are highlighted in a Y-configuration for which a high-speed line will go to the West Midlands.
The line will split in two to or near Birmingham, with a branch going west from the Pennines to Manchester and Scotland and another going northeast to Sheffield, Leeds and Newcastle upon Tyne.
A single line will cross Scotland.
"It seems that this will be the best performance option" said a rail professional.
When it's over, the travel time between London and Edinburgh will be reduced to 2 hours 40 minutes.
The first branch, which will not open until 2025, will allow all passengers to travel between London and Birmingham in 49 minutes, compared to a one-hour journey currently.
The proposals will allow the train to travel at 400 km/h, making the UK network the fastest in the world.
The initial route is designed to allow 400m long trains that can carry 1100 people.
Up to 18 trains per hour can operate on a London - Birmingham line.
A terminal for 20,000 passengers per hour would be required.
Given the space constraints, it is expected that an existing station will be expanded to accommodate the high-speed network.
Rail industry experts say that only St Pancras International or Euston offers this opportunity.
Lord Adonis will announce whether or not he thinks the project should be put in place, but longer public consultations and planning procedures mean that a final decision will not be taken before a general election.
Even if it launches the machine, the network will have to be built part by part.
Trains will first be forced to run off high-speed lines on existing rails north of Birmingham, keeping travel times between London and Scotland longer than three hours.
This solution seems to be the best way to ensure a passage from aircraft to trains, constituting a reference point for the rail revolution.
