The separatist Abkhazia elected its president, Georgia denounces a "farce"
Abkhazia elected its president on Saturday, just over a year after Moscow's recognition of this pro-Russian separatist region of Georgia, while Tbilisi denounces a "farce".
Some 131,000 people were called to participate in this first election after the August 2008 Russian-Georgian war for the control of South Ossetia, another Georgian secessionist territory recognized by Russia.
The polling stations closed at 17:00 GMT.
The turnout was 58% a few hours before the closure, according to officials of the Abkhaz Electoral Commission.
The first provisional results were to be announced on the night of Saturday to Sunday.
The five candidates, including the outgoing President, Sergei Bagapch, categorically reject the idea of reunification with Georgia, which condemned the holding of the election.
These elections are a farce.
For his part, Georgian President Mikheil Saakashvili, "regrets that Abkhazia has fallen under the total occupation of Russia," said his spokesman, Manana Manjgaladze.
Apart from Russia, only Nicaragua and Venezuela have recognized the independence of this territory of 216,000 inhabitants, while the rest of the world considers it part of Georgia illegally occupied by Russian troops.
After separating from Georgia during the 1992-1993 conflict, which killed several thousand people, Abkhazia seeks to show through this election that it is ready to join the international community.
This process is a step in our new life, our new era as an independent state, told AFP Svetlana Kvartchia, a 54-year-old historian, who claimed to have voted for Mr. Bagapch.
She was among the voters who went to the polling station in a school in Sukhumi, the capital, in a nice white building with some palm trees in front of the entrance.
The issue of Russian domination is at the heart of the presidential elections in this region with magnificent landscapes on the Black Sea.
Large panels showing Mr Bagapch alongside Russian President and Prime Minister Dmitri Medvedev and Vladimir Putin are installed throughout this small territory of 216,000 inhabitants.
In Gali, in the western part of the country, the district chief, Beslan Archba, gave a warm welcome to Russian officials who had come to monitor the election.
We, the Abkhaz people, are grateful, he said during a small ceremony, referring to Moscow's support, in particular the decision to recognize Abkhazia's independence.
I hope that your country will soon be recognized by the United Nations," said Alexey Ostrovski, a member of the Russian parliament, raising a glass of vodka.
For its part, the opposition represented by former Vice-President Raoul Khadjimba and two businessmen, Zaous Ardzinba and Beslan Boutba, in the election criticizes the agreements concluded with Moscow last year, as the one transferring to Russia the control over the Abkhaz railways for 10 years.
The fifth candidate, Vitali Bganba, claims that he does not support the current power or the opposition.
A 50% majority plus one vote is required to win the election.
If no candidate reaches this threshold, a second round must be organised within two weeks.
