The 62-year-old photographer, known for his star photos, will be tried on 15 and 16 April 2010 for abuse of weakness, an offence punishable by a maximum penalty of three years' imprisonment and a fine of 375,000 euros.
This decision means that there will be a trial in this case worthy of a saga on one of the richest families in France, in which mother and daughter tear themselves apart while holding the reins of the L'Oréal cosmetics empire.
But the 15th Correctional Chamber also ordered that a medical expertise of Liliane Bettencourt, 87 years old, should be conducted collegially by three doctors.
The heir and principal shareholder of L'Oréal has always refused to submit to such an examination, in any case not under the conditions proposed by the Nanterre Public Prosecutor's Office during the investigation.
The doctors appointed on Friday will have to submit a report before March 10, 2010 stating in particular whether Liliane Bettencourt was able to find himself in a state of weakness and at what times.
I think she'll submit to it.
I'll talk to him about it, said at the end of the hearing Ms. Bettencourt's lawyer, Georges Kiejman.
For his part, Françoise Bettencourt-Meyers' lawyer, Olivier Metzner, welcomed the court's decision.
This is excellent news (...) The expertise will show that he (Mr. Banier) manipulated this elderly lady who needs to be protected," he said.
For the past two years, Liliane Bettencourt's only daughter has brought criminal charges against François-Marie Banier, photographer and artist touch-all, whom she accuses of having taken advantage of her mother's weakness for years to obtain a billion euros in donations, in the form of cheques, life insurance contracts or masters' paintings.
For her part, Liliane Bettencourt has always refuted having been manipulated by the photographer, whom she considers to be a long-time friend.
While the court had to consider the admissibility of Ms.Bettencourt-Meyers' case, lawyers' pleadings sometimes turned out to be a big family unpack on Friday.
For example, Liliane Bettencourt's lawyer referred to three letters sent by her client (in 1999, 2003 and 2005) to her notary, in which she claimed to be wary of Françoise Bettencourt-Meyers' husband.
In the letter dated 2003, Liliane Bettencourt added, according to the lawyer: "Can you explain to my daughter that I wrote to Banier once, twice a day for fifteen years.
Françoise, I've never been able to talk to her since her marriage."
For its part, the Nanterre Public Prosecutor's Office once again found that the complainant was not admissible, especially since a guardianship judge had refused in recent days to grant her application to initiate legal protection proceedings for her mother.
Liliane Bettencourt "has full capacity to take legal action, she is not under protection and has no guardian.
No one else has to act in his place," said Marie-Chrsitine Daubigney, representative of the Public Prosecutor's Office.
The court finally decided that it would decide once the trial had taken place on the admissibility of Ms. Bettencourt-Meyers.
A managerial revolution or an end to economic intelligence?
If nothing changes in the governance of large French companies, our fight for the development of economic intelligence will have been in vain...
For more than ten years, the attitude of the management of large companies towards its employees, recalls the position of companies vis-à-vis consumers before the marketing revolution: it is a matter of making employees adhere to "values" determined from above as it once was, to impose on consumers products designed by the technicians of the factory.
By putting the customer at the heart of the company, the marketing revolution has put the strategies of conquering markets back at the place... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products disconnected from customer preferences factors returns regularly!
Demobilization of employees can lead to death demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only the emerging part of a much more general phenomenon that particularly affects executives.
This demobilisation seriously undermines the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, including R&D and, more importantly, economic intelligence.
In fact, EI "requires from all stakeholders (...) a proactive approach and a forward-looking vision"; it requires a commitment from employees that authoritarian management revenues totally contradict.
That is why we call for a managerial revolution that would put employees at the centre of the company's concerns in the same way as the customer.
The relative usefulness of internal opinion surveys
Will internal opinion surveys – such as the questionnaire submitted by Orange to its employees – encourage this revolution in managerial practices?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
- First of all because I was able to see that, in the face of a new situation, any structure finally comes, after many detours, to do first... what it has always done.
- Second, because authoritarianism – one of the pathologies of power – grows in proportion to the importance of its own failures.
- Finally, because most leaders have a simplistic view of human behaviour.
From the great engineering schools, they have a mechanistic interpretation of psychology.
They adopt, out of intellectual comfort, the old behaviorist theory, recently reactivated by the US "neurosciences" and widely disseminated, without their knowledge, by the institutes of studies and the media.
Thus, by suggesting that it is possible to handle the "leviers" (sic) of executive engagement, a recent survey by Ipsos published in Le Figaro.fr strengthens the leaders in a posture of mechanistic governance, inappropriate to today's world.
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern enterprises requires the adoption of a finalist vision of human behaviour.
It consists of integrating, in any reasoning or practice of governance, a fundamental observation: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it clearly appears as a means of realizing part of their dreams, ambitions and projects.
Currently, only studies resulting from the Motivational Analysis adopt this concept of employee motivations.
These studies have shown that they judge their company on the basis of a predetermined doxa that allows them, through their perceived image of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to carry out their life projects.
Through the identification and measurement of these mobilization factors, company managers can monitor, predict and anticipate their "social performance" and put their human resources management "at the place".
They thus create a favourable environment for the concerted development of robust and effective economic intelligence.
Oslo's speech: the "just war" is praiseworthy to Obama on the right
The American right welcomed on Friday Barack Obama's speech in Oslo the previous day, satisfied that the 2009 Nobel Peace Prize had defended the concept of "just war" against the enemies of the United States.
The Conservatives, who had broached Obama's award on 9 October, this time applauded the presidential speech, as did Sarah Palin, a former vice-president in the 2008 elections.
I liked what he said, said Mrs. Palin, the agry of the right wing of the Republican party, to the daily USA Today, adding that she herself addressed the theme of war "sometimes necessary" in her memoirs that have just been published.
The war is, of course, the last thing I think the Americans want to do, but it is necessary.
We need to stop these terrorists all over there, she said.
Obama, who inherited the two wars of his predecessor George W. Bush in Iraq and Afghanistan, tried Thursday in Oslo to justify the use of force, a way to explain his decision to send an additional 30,000 soldiers to Afghanistan nine days earlier.
Another opponent of Obama, Newt Gingrich, felt that the president had done "very good work" in Oslo.
I thought the speech was really very good, said the former Speaker of the House of Representatives, who particularly appreciated the mention of "the existence of evil in the world" in the presidential speech.
On some sides, I found this quite historic speech, said Mr. Gingrich, who was interviewed on the radio program "The Takeaway".
The former elected candidate, considered by some as a possible candidate for the Republican nomination for the 2012 presidential election, said he was delighted to have seen "a left-wing president" remind members of the Nobel Committee "that they would not be free and would not be able to award a peace prize if the use of force did not exist".
For Michael Gerson, George W. Bush's former columnist pen at the Washington Post, Obama gave "a very American speech."
In addition to presenting himself as a "citizen of the world" as "he always does", "he spoke like an American president", reminding Europeans "that they live in a security bubble that they have not created and that they do not do much to preserve it", said Mr Gerson.
Among the few to the right to be unconvinced, a Bush-era hawk, former UN Ambassador John Bolton, described the speech as "ternal, uninspired and uninspired" on the National Review Online site.
On the left of the president, Democratic Representative Dennis Kucinich expressed alarm that Barack Obama was justifying the use of force.
When one envelopes war in the notion of justice, one can easily justify the massacre of innocents, he warned.
The centre-left press, however, remained praiseful of the president.
The Los Angeles Times, while continuing to believe that the Nobel was prematurely attributed to Mr. Obama, described his speech as "superproduction" even for a speaker known for his talent.
Oslo's speech "should serve as a road map to guide international decisions against conflict, poverty and oppression", the Californian daily inflamed itself.
Obama "made the right speech," the New York Times said, "considering it both dark and uplifting."
Routers: three marathons for an agreement that saves Christmas supplies
After three marathon negotiations, the road trade unions and TLF, the only employers' organisation to have remained to the end, reached an agreement on Friday night that ended the strike slogan and the threat to Christmas supplies.
During the signing session on Friday night, the Secretary of State for Transport, Dominique Bussereau, "rejoiceed" this agreement, after several negotiating sessions, started Wednesday morning.
After a second night of discussions the negotiators had left in the early morning on Friday, hoping to quickly sign the text of the agreement at the end of the morning.
Even if three employers' organizations (FNTR, Unostra, OTRE) had slammed the door.
But it took even more than six hours of a meeting started at 11:00 a.m. for everyone to agree and for the text to be signed at 6:00 p.m.
The conflict "would have been very detrimental to business" and "there was a fear that it would disrupt the end-of-year holidays," said Mr. Bussereau.
The text provides for an increase in wages of 4% for the lowest wages (in local and regional road transport), and 2.9% for the highest (international transport).
In hourly rates, for low-wage earners, "from 8.72 euros to 9.06 euros.
It's not a big deal, but we're going a long way, explained Patrice Clos (FO).
We're going to order our activists that there are no blockages, no blockades of the supply centres.
But we can still have some recalcitrants that are not happy, he added.
Philippe Grilllot, President of TLF, praised "a good deal", even though it was "difficult to concede increases on high wages given the international competition".
According to him, the increases will be of the order of 170 euros monthly for low wages and of 100 to 120 euros for the highest.
This is the agreement of common sense and respect for employees, said Maxime Dumont (CFDT), while Thierry Douine (CFTC) welcomed "a historic agreement".
Richard Jaubert (CGT) referred to "an acceptable compromise".
The agreement also provides for the upgrading of travel costs by 3%, and the maintenance of the general state of road transport in the first half of 2010, which will, in particular, address the question of a 13th month and a modernisation of the collective agreement.
Mr Bussereau recalled that "a reduction of EUR 100 million in employers' costs" had been the subject of a governmental amendment to the draft amending finance law for 2009, which was voted on the night of Thursday to Friday by the National Assembly.
The government will ask the Senate to vote "in identical terms".
TLF's signature allows the agreement to apply initially to companies that are members of TLF, and in a second stage to the entire profession, if the Minister of Labour has extended it.
It will take place "as soon as possible", Mr. Bussereau said.
Opposition from employers' organizations can only delay the process.
The FNTR denounced a "dupes market", as the EUR 100 million "had already been promised to the sector to offset part of the carbon tax".
The Secretary of State for Transport has forced us to negotiate urgently, not in conclusion of a shared analysis, but in order not to upset the turkey eaters of the next New Year's Eve, deplored the Unostra.
For Otre, the agreement is likely to "deep the grave of a very large number of SMEs in the sector in the next 12 months".
