Turkish justice dissolves pro-Kurdish party, with heavy consequences
The Turkish Constitutional Court ruled on Friday the dissolution of the country's main pro-Kurdish party, a decision that was immediately followed by expressions of anger in the Kurdish community, in the south-eastern part of the country and in Istanbul.
This decision could greatly complicate the task of the government, which has just reached out to the Kurdish community in an attempt to end 25 years of conflict.
The Party for a Democratic Society (DTP) was dissolved because it had become a "home of activities detrimental to the independence of the State and its indivisible unity", said to the press the President of the Court Hasim Kiliç, after four days of deliberations.
The decision was taken unanimously by the 11 judges, while a qualified majority of seven votes was required to pronounce the dissolution, said Mr.Kiliç, adding that 37 of the party's executives, including its president Ahmet Türk and MP Aysel Tugluk, are banned from political life for a period of five years.
The judge also announced the lifting of the parliamentary immunity enjoyed by Mr. Türk and Ms. Tugluk and the confiscation by the Treasury of the party's property.
The DTP has 21 seats in Parliament (out of 550).
Its leaders had warned before the verdict that MPs would leave Parliament rather than sit as parliamentarians without a label.
The decision follows a procedure launched in 2007 by the prosecutor of the Court of Cassation Abdurrahman Yalçinkaya, who accuses the DTP of obeying the "guidelines" of the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK), considered a terrorist organization by Ankara and many countries.
Many observers believe that the DTP is the legal political showcase of the PKK rebels.
However, the party asserts that it has "no organic ties" with the PKK but refuses to qualify it as a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate with it.
The Court's verdict comes at a time when the government has just reached out to the Kurdish community by proposing a series of measures strengthening its rights, in an attempt to tarnish the Kurds' support for the PKK and put an end to the conflict.
The DTP leaders had claimed that a dissolution could lead to an increase in tensions in the southeastern Anatolian region, where numerous demonstrations against the conditions of detention of PKK leader Abdullah Öcalan have degenerated into clashes with the police in recent weeks.
As soon as the justice system was announced, a thousand demonstrators gathered in front of the DTP premises in Diyarbakir, the great city of the south-east inhabited mainly by Kurds.
Law enforcement fired tear gas grenades and used water cannons, while protesters were throwing molotov cocktails or stones, with slings.
Some 100 people also demonstrated in Istanbul.
After the verdict, Mr. Türk stated that the decision of the justice system would "deepen despair".
Turkey cannot solve this issue (Kurdish, ndlr) by banning a party, he told the press.
The government, formed by a party from the Islamist movement, also deplored the decision.
We are opposed as a matter of principle to the closure of the parties.
It doesn't solve anything, said Energy Minister Taner Yildiz.
This decision is a total torpedo of the democratic openness launched by the government, said political analyst Ahmet Insel.
One can, of course, expect a reaction from the PKK, he added.
On Thursday, the PKK claimed responsibility for an attack that had killed seven soldiers three days earlier in northern Turkey, one of the deadliest in recent months.
The first snows can fall
What Wolfgang Brauburger wants is a harsh winter.
But the head of the road clearing and sanding service (FES) makes it clear that it is not to bother the citizens.
It's just so that agents can test the vehicle technique and learn how to master them.
And according to the meterologists, it might be for this weekend.
More than 300 agents and 120 vehicles stand ready to attack snow and ice.
The FES follows a very elaborate plan here.
Mr Brauburger explains that as soon as he starts snowing on the city of Frankfurt and temperatures fall below zero, large sand-blasting vehicles travel 20 main routes (named itineraries A).
This includes high-traffic streets, major arteries, such as the Neue Weg and the Hanauer Landstraße.
Fire services, public transport routes, pedestrian areas and sloping streets such as the Atzelbergstraße are also included.
The FES officers begin their service at three o'clock in the morning.
In case of need, the 1040 kilometres of road must be salted with a road fondue that adheres well, in 3 hours maximum time.
This is why the service of the FES starts at 3am "so that the roads are cleared when the traffic of daily migration begins".
Where it gets harder, it's when the snow starts to fall at 7:30 in the morning.
This poses problems, we are told by the head of the road clearing and sanding service "because no motorist is willing to let the dirty vehicles pass".
Then, if it no longer snows, we take care of access roads and service roads - such as the Rat-Beil-Straße.
Secondary lanes and side streets come last.
Mr. Brauburger knows that this still leads to a few complaints.
At five o'clock in the morning, the walking team of the FES set out to clear the areas deemed dangerous and the passageways as a matter of priority.
As for cycle paths, the services of the FES are generally not able to deal with them.
Mr Braubburger pointed out that there was a special service in Frankfurt to monitor the state of the bridges between 22:00 and 04:30.
As the ice is formed very quickly on these surfaces, the salting vehicles intervene as soon as the temperature drops below 2 degrees.
This special service may also be used by the police if necessary.
The cradle of dinosaurs
The Tawa hallae resembled other carnivorous dinosaurs: the biped was about 2 metres long for 1.50m high, its hind limbs were strong, its elongated skull was provided with sharp and curved teeth, its short arms ended in sickle claws and it had a long tail.
If this species had lived a few million years later, it would not have had anything exceptional.
But, as Sertling Nesbitt reports from the University of Texas at Austin and his colleagues in Thursday's Science magazine, the Tawa hallae is one of the first dinosaurs with these morphological characteristics.
This animal lived 215 million years ago in New Mexico, which at the time was part of the land emerging from the supercontinent, the Pangee, and was towards the equator.
Sertling Nesbitt says the discovery of the Tawa sheds new light on the evolution of the early dinosaurs.
Indeed, it informs us about the kinship, the distribution and the characteristics of the latter.
It was in 2006 that Sertling Nesbitt undertook excavations with other paleontologists at the Gohst Ranch site in northern New Mexico.
Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History and member of the excavation team tells them that sometimes they find a dozen bones in a day which is absolutely unique for a sedimentary layer dating from the Trias.
Scientists quickly realized that some of these bones belonged to a new species.
The excavations updated the remains of five specimens.
A discovery that confirms the theories concerning the early evolution of dinosaurs.
The researchers named him Tawa from the Indian word Hopi for the sun god.
For Sterling Nesbitt, this is an exceptional discovery: dinosaur fossils from the Trias are extremely rare and are limited to a few incomplete bone fragments.
Not all paleontology experts share this enthusiasm.
For example, Martin Sander of the University of Bonn does not find this discovery to be particularly spectacular, but he points out that it confirms some theories concerning the early evolution of dinosaurs.
According to the current state of knowledge, dinosaurs appeared on Earth about 230 million years ago.
Most of the oldest fossils, however, are fragmented and incomplete, making it very difficult to classify the very first dinosaurs.
The experts wonder, among other things, at what time the saurians were divided into three major groups of evolution: the theropods (carnivores) which include the tyrannosaure and the velociraptor which appeared later and descended from the birds, the sauropods, quadrupeds with long necks, and those related to them and the herbivores ornithischians of which species such as tritratops and stegosaurus are part.
According to the studies of S. Nesbitt and his colleagues, the Tawa is one of the first theropods.
This species has an interesting relationship of both primitive and developed characteristics, says S. Nesbitt.
The researchers found evidence that the Tawa hallae had small airbags in its bones at the level of the skull, as did the birds that are descendants of the theropods.
These small pockets of air facilitate the breathing of birds relative to mammals.
It appears that in Tawa hallae, the vertebrae were also partially filled with air.
According to Randall Irmis, the Tawa is one of the oldest theropods with small aerial bags in its bones.
Since the related lineage of the huge sauropods also had airbags and light bones, it may be thought that their common ancestor already had this beneficial innovation.
Three successive waves of migration to North America.
As the most primitive known dinosaurs lived in South America, the researchers concluded that the saurians had appeared there.
As a result, the three major evolutionary lines were divided and spread from South America to the rest of the world, i.e., all the lands that formed the Pangee supercontinent.
This seems to be confirmed by the fact that the team of paleontologists also discovered the remains of two other theropods that are not particularly related to him.
The three species cannot descend from a common ancestor who would have migrated, advance the researchers.
Alan Turner of the Natural History Museum of New York and co-author of Science Studies magazine says there would have been at least three waves of migration to North America.
There are, of course, some contradictions.
Martin Sander, a paleontologist in Bonn, says that there is an even older species, the silesaure, which lived in present-day Poland and belongs to a group related to dinosaurs.
According to him, this could give a misconception because there are a large number of dinosaur fossils in South America that have been preserved while virtually none are found on other continents.
On the other hand, how dinosaurs have managed to become the dominant tetrapod of the secondary era when they came from a relatively rare collateral line of the reptile branch, remains a mystery today.
At the time of the Trias, dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, such as the ancestors of today's crocodiles and many other saurians.
Towards the end of the Trias the dinosaurs spread all over the planet thus favoring the development of many new species while others, which were related to them, disappeared between the Trias and the Jurassic.
Such success, however, is not eternal.
To explain this transformation, Martin Sander sees two hypotheses.
There may have been a massive extinction from which dinosaurs survived randomly while other reptiles would have disappeared.
Or, then, dinosaurs were better suited and they were able to eliminate competition on the ground.
In any case, such a success is not eternal.
150 million years later, the fall of a favourite meteorite's development of a group of animals which had also developed during the Trias and which since then vegetated in the shadow: they were mammals.
Solidarity from Vienna to Sao Paulo
