The new "Silicon-valley"
For a long time it had the reputation of a secret city, forbidden to Western visitors.
Zelenograd, one of the ten districts of Moscow, was, under the Soviet regime, a place for the search for secret weapons, under strict supervision.
Today, with its 216 000 inhabitants 37 km from the centre of Moscow, the municipality has the reputation of being the Soviet "Silicon Valley".
Important production and research sites in micro- and nanoelectronics are located there.
As early as September 2008, Zelenograd representatives established links with Riedberg, the site of the Francfortian sciences – with the university institutes and the companies of the Frankfurt Innovation Centre (FIZ).
There have been reciprocal meetings and last Wednesday representatives of Zelenograd and Riedberg have ratified a "Protocol of Close Collaboration".
The signatories were the deputy mayor of Moscow Juri Rosljak and the prefect Anatoly Smimov of Zelenograd for the Russian delegation, Edwin Schwarz project section head for Frankfurt.
In 2010, representatives of IFZ and SMEs, whose main focus is scientific research, will go to Zelenograd for a seminar.
Scientific exchange
This is a sustainable scientific exchange.
But also economic relations.
It will allow IFZ companies to enter the expanding Russian market.
On the other hand, Russian scientific companies want contracts in Germany.
Zelenograd is the headquarters of famous Soviet research institutes and societies.
There are the Moscow Institute of Electrical Engineering, the major Sitronics and Rosssijskaja-Elektronika companies.
The commune was founded in 1958 as a "planned socialist city" for weapons research.
Zelenograd (literal translation "Green City") takes its name from the wooded hills at the heart of which the research centres are located.
The S21 project: a brake for Stuttgart
The scope of the Stuttgart 21 project cannot be placed sufficiently high.
For his supporters it is nothing less than "new heart of Europe".
S21 is much more than the burial of a railway station, more than a colossal construction project that will plunge the heart of the capital of Baden-Württemberg into desperate chaos of construction sites for about ten years.
Stuttgart 21 was born from the spirit of the 1980s.
The head-of-line stations, with tracks ending in the middle of the city, had the reputation at the time of being the relics of 19th-century transport technology that acted as a brake hoof of modern rail traffic because it once took a long time to move the locomotives from the rear to the front.
Arrival, short stop, departure – that's what you have to do.
That is why the head-of-line stations must disappear: in Frankfurt and Munich.
And also in Stuttgart: a train crossing station, which is about halfway on the Trans-European Railway Magistral between Paris and Budapest / Bratislava hence the slogan "heart of Europe".
The realization of the S21 project will really begin, although the visions of the 1980s have not been compatible with reality for a long time.
Even the most ambitious planners acknowledged that the cost of burying the station in the respective capitals of Hesse and Bavaria was exorbitant.
In fact, head-of-line stations no longer pose any real problems of entry and exit since there are modern, reversible trains with railcars and pilot cars at both ends.
However, the Stuttgart 21 project is now being launched alongside the new route of the intercity line towards Ulm.
Regional and communal policies have prevailed.
The railway company is of the part because it is the taxpayer who makes the costs of the risks of the largest infrastructure project in the Federal Republic and not the public undertaking.
From an urban point of view, this project is relatively well justified.
