These include mental disorders such as borderline or depression, but also migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis, Alzheimer's disease or head trauma.
Surprisingly, under certain conditions even the brain of healthy people is subject to hallucinations.
The hallucinations, according to Kasten, consist of fragments of memories that are normally inhibited.
They take shape when the brain areas that treat sensory perceptions, are hyperactive or not sufficiently refreshed; when our brain heats but also when there is no stimulation.
Drugs can trigger this state as well as brain injury or psychosis.
But also lack of stimulus, stress, sorrows of love or other exceptional mental states.
In recent studies, one third of participants acknowledge having experienced hallucinations at least once in their lives.
In summer 2005 Sarah K. is 16 years old, lives in a small town in Mecklenburg-Pomerania and goes to high school.
A young girl all to do normal to tell the truth.
If there weren't images and voices.
During recreation, a young boy, thin, with long brown hair, may speak to him.
When she replies her comrades look at her, astonished – no one else sees or hears this boy.
They think this shy girl is a lunatic dreamer, but Sarah K doesn't dream, she's sure.
She is awake, hears and sees this boy just as she sees and hears the girl sitting next to her on the bench.
She can even perceive her presence momentarily.
It's a nice feeling, she finds this young man friendly.
Am I crazy?, she sometimes wonders.
But she knows that this young man and the other visions are not real and that they will disappear again.
At night the apparitions are, in general, frightening.
Often visions are heavy.
When she is in class, she may not be able to take the course because the teacher is just presenting a new student in his eyes and ears while he is invisible to others and the teacher is obviously explaining equations to the table.
At night the apparitions are, in general, frightening.
When, in the darkness of her room, she waits for sleep that arrives too rarely and far too late, she often cannot make the distinction if she is awake or dreaming already, if the images she sees, the grim faces or the girl with bloody cuts on her arms and legs are in front of her eyes open or closed.
Leave me alone, she shouts to these creatures.
She doesn't talk to her parents or her friends, they think she's crazy.
Fall 2009. Sarah K. is now 20 years old.
She got her baccalaureate last year and she lives with her friend.
A year ago hallucinations stopped.
Ever since she came into contact with the psychologist Kasten, she knows very well that she's not crazy.
Madness is also a work of art of despair.
When someone is socially isolated or does not have enough stimulation, the probability is high that they will have hallucinations after a certain time.
I guess the brain isn't busy enough, so there's animation.
Sarah K., a single daughter, was afraid of other children when she was little and often played alone.
Her hallucinations began when she learned at the age of 13, that the man she called dad, since she was of thinking age, was not her real father.
These are the same brain zones that are active for visual and acoustic hallucinations, and for real impressions and noises, so it is very difficult for people like Sarah K to make the difference between illusion and reality. "Every experience," according to Kasten "is taking place in the brain, reality is formed from there.
The hallucinations are also images that form in the brain, which is why they seem so real."
For Kasten, night dreams are also a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people are not fundamentally different from those in acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenia, the mentally healthy person is able to recognize that fantasies are not real images.
That's why Kasten advises his patients to cherish hallucinations as a particular talent.
There's only one step between dream and hallucination.
In our world too consciously focused, unfortunately, we tend to take the imaginary experiences for pathologies, according to Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor at Heidelberg and doctor head of the psychiatric and psychotherapy clinic at Florence Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
Psychosis is a serious, painful disease, but it also contains something positive, creative - madness is a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard studied the form of so-called oniroid experience, a particular form of the modification of consciousness awakened by the dream.
Oniroid experiences are very complex semi-dreves that are perceived as real by the person who lives them and that he cannot differentiate from the dream even when he is in a state of awakening.
The oniroid state of consciousness manifests itself during trauma or in situations of extreme pathologies as for patients with polyradiculopathy who fully consciously experience motor paralysis.
According to Schmidt-Degenhard, when a human being is threatened by a loss of self and of the world, due to a total and lasting inability to move, he replaces this real situation that harms his life, with his own imaginary world that is dissociated from reality.
It's a state of mental boundary between dream and hallucination.
As it is not possible to overcome the situation in reality, a change of world takes place but the real situation is represented in the imagination.
It is, in fact, an intense form of means and interpretation, in an intolerable situation in itself, an organizational capacity that is given to us, to us men, so as not to sink into the nothingness of the loss of consciousness.
Everything is real even later in memories.
Zurich's Peter Cornelius Classen, art historian, also describes his oniroid experiences in his book "Changing the Heart" as an action to safeguard the soul.
He is 49 years old, at the time when his consciousness leaves for a journey several days after the operation of a heart valve followed by a transplant; during this time, his body is condemned to remain motionless in resuscitation.
Claussen plunges into a world he has created of all kinds, visits foreign places, travels through time. He sees himself as an old man in a railway sanatorium, a robot at his bedside looking after his health.
He lives in the Middle Ages among nobles who make drugs based on blood.
He is taken by a Greek motorcycle who takes him to his country, he surfs with his hospital bed in the neve of the Alps and meets a Korean mafia.
He completely absorbs himself into this imaginary world, everything is real even later in his memories.
According to Claussen, these domestic travels are fundamentally different from any dream.
The dream is a completely different state, he writes describing what he has experienced.
On the contrary of dreams, memories from mental travels are extremely clear and very detailed even years later.
It can even be said that they are much more distinct and intensive than the real experience.
The intensity of this experience brings out the horizon of our other daily experiences, according to psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
Ultimately, the oniroid delusions, psychoses, hallucinations and psychedelic experiences show us how fragile our inner representations of the external reality are even in a state of watch.
Any change in the state of consciousness, sums up the psychologist Kasten "may cause a distortion of what we call reality."
An experience that can also be quite enriching.
