75% of working mothers had work problems due to their maternity
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for young generation women who want to be mothers.
This is revealed by the study "Fécondité et carrière professionnel des femmes en Espagne", carried out by the CSIC in collaboration with the Instituto de la Mujer.
The survey, conducted on 9,737 women aged 15 to 75, leaves no room for doubt: 75 per cent of working mothers had their professional careers limited because of maternity.
The study indicates that there are many differences in the beginning of couple life and the number of children, whether or not the woman works and the type of employment held.
Those who do not work outside the home, work part-time or have unstable work, get married earlier, have their first pregnancy earlier and have more children.
On the other hand, women in stable employment, mainly in the public sector, push back entry into marriage and first pregnancy, and have fewer children.
Women between the ages of 35 and 49 with fixed work have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after moving in as a couple. This figure rises to 4.1 for those working in the public sector."These data show that women with stable jobs have needed more time in their lives to get it, which has led them to delay the union and arrival of children.
In addition, the type of employment that is exercised largely influences maternity, but less the date of the beginning of a common life," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
Educational attainment is another factor that widens the age gap between women and their first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of education, the more they get married and have their first child late.
The difference is also maintained among women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49 age group, those with elementary and higher education were mothers for the first time at 25.1 and 32.1 years on average, respectively.
"Another distinction also emerges between women, depending on their level of education.
While those who have completed elementary education get married and have their first child before finding a stable job, those who have completed middle or higher education reverse this program and give priority to obtaining stable work as a prerequisite for marriage and the arrival of a child," says Delgado.
